{"type":"text","timestamp":1777742300812,"sessionID":"ses_21652b159ffetKEIjuAlMIK8KR","part":{"id":"prt_de9b2af19001GU2JT41OG9xb9w","messageID":"msg_de9b2a512001nvZtbDZU07O8Ok","sessionID":"ses_21652b159ffetKEIjuAlMIK8KR","type":"text","text":"Hypothesis written to `cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260502-001-r1s0.yaml`.\n\n**Summary:** The proposal eliminates the 1-cycle load-use stall by forwarding the MEM-stage dmem read data directly into the EX-stage operand muxes. This is a classic textbook optimization — the dmem_rdata arrives combinationally during the MEM stage, so a dependent instruction entering EX in the same cycle can consume it immediately without waiting for the WB-stage register write.\n\n**Expected impact:** +5% fitness (IPC gains from eliminated stall cycles, slightly offset by a marginally longer critical path through the added forwarding mux).\n\n**Files touched:** `forward_unit.sv` (detect load-use forwarding), `ex_stage.sv` (new forwarding source + byte-extract), `hazard_unit.sv` (remove load-use stall), `core.sv` (top-level wiring).","time":{"start":1777742294809,"end":1777742300811}}}
