22:   in EX. The BHT is updated synchronously from EX with the actual branch\n23:   outcome using saturating up/down counters. This should increase IPC by\n24:   ~15-25% for CoreMark, with a modest LUT cost (~128 FFs for the BHT, plus\n25:   prediction/mispredict logic).\n26: expected_impact:\n27:   fitness_delta_pct: 12\n28:   confidence: medium\n29: changes:\n30:   - file: rtl/bht.sv\n31:     description: \"New module: 64-entry 2-bit saturating-counter bimodal BHT. Combinational read port for ID stage, synchronous update port driven by EX branch resolution.\"\n32:   - file: rtl/id_stage.sv\n33:     description: \"Integrate BHT lookup. On predicted-taken (or JAL), assert predict_redirect and compute redirect target = PC+imm. Pass predicted_taken flag through ID/EX for EX-stage verification.\"\n34:   - file: rtl/if_stage.sv\n35:     description: \"Accept predict_redirect and predict_target from ID stage as a second redirect source (lower priority than EX redirect). Redirect PC when predict_redirect is asserted.\"\n36:   - file: rtl/ex_stage.sv\n37:     description: \"Compare predicted direction (from ID/EX predicted_taken field) with actual branch resolution. On mispredict, assert mispredict_redirect to flush IF+ID and correct PC. Generate BHT update signals (update_valid, update_index, update_taken).\"\n38:   - file: rtl/hazard_unit.sv\n39:     description: \"Accept mispredict_redirect input; treat identically to current EX redirect (assert flush_if and flush_id to kill wrong-path instructions following a mispredicted branch).\"\n40:   - file: rtl/core.sv\n41:     description: \"Wire predict_redirect and predict_target from ID to IF; wire mispredict_redirect from EX to hazard_unit; instantiate bht module and connect read/update ports between ID, EX, and BHT.\"\n42:   - file: rtl/core_pkg.sv\n43:     description: \"Add predicted_taken bit to id_ex_t struct so EX stage can compare prediction against actual branch outcome.\"\n\n(End of file - total 43 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"id: hyp-20260502-003-r1s2\ntitle: \"Bimodal BHT with ID-stage branch redirect\"\ncategory: predictor\nmotivation: |\n  The baseline 5-stage pipeline resolves all branches in EX with a 2-cycle\n  taken-penalty (IF+ID flush). JAL/JALR also pay the same penalty despite\n  JAL being unconditional. Adding a small bimodal branch history table that\n  predicts branch direction in the ID stage reduces the taken-branch penalty\n  to 0 cycles for correctly-predicted branches, increasing IPC significantly\n  for CoreMark's loop-heavy workload at minimal hardware cost.\nhypothesis: |\n  Add a 64-entry 2-bit saturating-counter bimodal BHT indexed by PC[7:2].\n  The BHT is read combinationally in the ID stage in parallel with decode.\n  When the prediction is \"taken\" (counter MSB=1) or the instruction is JAL,\n  the ID stage computes the target (PC+imm, already available from imm_gen)\n  and asserts a predict_redirect signal back to the IF stage, causing the PC\n  to jump to the target on the next clock edge. The predicted direction is\n  stored in the ID/EX register. In EX, the actual branch outcome is compared\n  against the prediction; on mispredict, the EX stage flushes IF+ID and\n  redirects to the correct target (same mechanism as current EX redirect).","truncated":false,"loaded":[]},"title":"cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260502-003-r1s2.yaml","time":{"start":1777742340338,"end":1777742340344}},"id":"prt_de9b359d1001MC4Cd7ah0BU6C9","sessionID":"ses_21652b059ffezeCHMDlF3WVOZk","messageID":"msg_de9b34d75001b3hrui6QZ2nkef"}}
